Claims CLAIMS What is claimed is: 1. A system comprising: a data processor; and a prediction-based trajectory planning module, executable by the data processor, the prediction-based trajectory planning module being configured to perform a prediction- based trajectory planning operation for autonomous vehicles, the prediction-based trajectory planning operation being configured to: receive training data and ground truth data from a training data collection system, the training data including perception data and context data corresponding to human driving behaviors; perform a training phase to train a trajectory prediction module using the training data; receive perception data associated with a host vehicle; and perform an operational phase configured to extract host vehicle feature data and proximate vehicle context data from the perception data, generate a proposed trajectory for the host vehicle, use the trained trajectory prediction module to generate predicted trajectories for each of one or more proximate vehicles near the host vehicle based on the proposed host vehicle trajectory, determine if the proposed trajectory for the host vehicle will conflict with any of the predicted trajectories of the proximate vehicles, and modify the proposed trajectory for the host vehicle until conflicts are eliminated. 2. The system of claim 1 being further configured to filter and smooth the perception data. 3. The system of claim 1 being further configured to generate coordinate transformations of the perception data relative to the one or more proximate vehicles. 4. The system of claim 1 wherein the training data includes labeling data that includes context information defining directionality and rate behaviors of vehicles represented in the training data. 5. The system of claim 1 wherein the training data includes labeling data that includes context information defining directionality and rate behaviors of vehicles represented in the training data, the context data further defining a left turn, no turn, or a right turn. 6. The system of claim 1 wherein the perception data including data received from a sensor of a type from the group consisting of: a camera or image capture device, an inertial measurement unit (IMU), a Global Positioning System (GPS) transceiver, a RADAR unit, and a laser range finder/LIDAR unit. 7. The system of claim 1 being further configured to use regression to predict acceleration of a vehicle. 8. The system of claim 1 being further configured to determine if any of the predicted trajectories for the proximate vehicles may cause the host vehicle to violate a pre-defined goal based on a related score being below a minimum acceptable threshold. 9. The system of claim 1 wherein the proposed trajectory for the host vehicle is output to a vehicle control subsystem causing the host vehicle to follow the output proposed trajectory. 10. A method comprising: receiving training data and ground truth data from a training data collection system, the training data including perception data and context data corresponding to human driving behaviors; performing a training phase for training a trajectory prediction module using the training data; 

 receiving perception data associated with a host vehicle; and performing an operational phase for extracting host vehicle feature data and proximate vehicle context data from the perception data, generating a proposed trajectory for the host vehicle, using the trained trajectory prediction module to generate predicted trajectories for each of one or more proximate vehicles near the host vehicle based on the proposed host vehicle trajectory, determining if the proposed trajectory for the host vehicle will conflict with any of the predicted trajectories of the proximate vehicles, and modifying the proposed trajectory for the host vehicle until conflicts are eliminated. 11. The method of claim 10 including filtering and smoothing the perception data. 12. The method of claim 10 including generating coordinate transformations of the perception data relative to the one or more proximate vehicles. 13. The method of claim 10 wherein the training data includes labeling data that includes context information defining directionality and rate behaviors of vehicles represented in the training data. 14. The method of claim 10 wherein the training data includes labeling data that includes context information defining directionality and rate behaviors of vehicles represented in the training data, the context data further defining a left turn, no turn, or a right turn. 15. The method of claim 10 wherein the perception data including data received from a sensor of a type from the group consisting of: a camera or image capture device, an inertial measurement unit (IMU), a Global Positioning System (GPS) transceiver, a RADAR unit, and a laser range finder/LIDAR unit. 16. The method of claim 10 including using regression to predict acceleration of a vehicle. 17. The method of claim 10 including determining if any of the predicted trajectories for the proximate vehicles may cause the host vehicle to violate a pre-defined goal based on a related score being below a minimum acceptable threshold. 18. The method of claim 10 wherein the proposed trajectory for the host vehicle is output to a vehicle control subsystem causing the host vehicle to follow the output proposed trajectory. 19. A non-transitory machine-useable storage medium embodying instructions which, when executed by a machine, cause the machine to: receive training data and ground truth data from a training data collection system, the training data including perception data and context data corresponding to human driving behaviors; perform a training phase for training a trajectory prediction module using the training data; receive perception data associated with a host vehicle; and perform an operational phase for extracting host vehicle feature data and proximate vehicle context data from the perception data, generating a proposed trajectory for the host vehicle, using the trained trajectory prediction module to generate predicted trajectories for each of one or more proximate vehicles near the host vehicle based on the proposed host vehicle trajectory, determining if the proposed trajectory for the host vehicle will conflict with any of the predicted trajectories of the proximate vehicles, and modifying the proposed trajectory for the host vehicle until conflicts are eliminated. 20. The non-transitory machine-useable storage medium of claim 19 wherein the instructions are further configured to filter and smooth the perception data. 21. A system, comprising: 

 a training data collection system to collect training data including perception data corresponding to human driving behaviors from vehicles and drivers in real world traffic environments; and a prediction-based trajectory planning system trained based on context data extracted from the training data to generate a trajectory prediction for vehicles or objects proximate to a host vehicle based on perception data acquired by the host vehicle and based on a proposed trajectory for the host vehicle, wherein a trajectory for the host vehicle is determined by comparing the proposed trajectory for the host vehicle obtained using the trained prediction-based trajectory planning system with the trajectory prediction for vehicles or objects proximate to the host vehicle. 22. The system of claim 21, wherein the prediction-based trajectory planning system includes a machine learning system that includes parameters trained based on the context data extracted from the training data. 23. The system of claim 21, wherein the perception data acquired by the host vehicle includes feature data of the host vehicle and context data of proximate vehicles. 24. The system of claim 21, wherein the training data collection system is configured to classify the human driving behaviors into a plurality of scenarios with different labels indicating different driving scenarios. 25. The system of claim 21, wherein prediction-based trajectory planning system is further configured to determine a confidence level corresponding to a likelihood of the proximate vehicles to perform the predicted behavior. 26. The system of claim 21, wherein the perception data acquired by the host vehicle includes status and context information from the host vehicle to predict the behavior of the proximate vehicles that might have an influence on the host vehicle. 27. The system of claim 21, wherein the trajectory prediction includes an acceleration prediction obtained using a regression algorithm. 28. A system, comprising: a proposed trajectory generator to generate a proposed trajectory for a host vehicle; a trajectory prediction generator to generate predicted trajectories of proximate vehicles near the host vehicle based on a proposed trajectory for the host vehicle; a comparator to compare the proposed trajectory for the host vehicle with the predicted trajectories of the proximate vehicles; and a vehicle controller to decide whether to adjust speed or heading of the host vehicle based on the comparison of the proposed trajectory for the host vehicle and the predicted trajectories of the proximate vehicle. 29. The system of claim 28, wherein, if the comparison of the proposed trajectory for the host vehicle and the predicted trajectories of the proximate vehicle indicates the proposed trajectory for the host vehicle exceeds a minimum acceptable threshold, the proposed trajectory for the host vehicle is modified until the minimum acceptable threshold is satisfied. 30. The system of claim 28, wherein the predicted trajectories of proximate vehicles are generated based on training data including perception data corresponding to human driving behaviors from vehicles and drivers in real world traffic environments. 31. The system of claim 30, wherein the trajectory prediction generator includes a machine learning system that includes parameters trained based on context data in which the host vehicle is operating. 32. The system of claim 28, wherein the trajectory prediction includes an acceleration prediction obtained using a regression algorithm. 33. The system of claim 28, wherein the trajectory prediction generator is further configured to determine a confidence level corresponding to a likelihood of the proximate vehicles to take the predicted trajectories. 34. A system, comprising: a memory to store executable instructions; and a processor in communication with the memory, configured to read the executable instructions from the memory to: generate a proposed trajectory for a host vehicle; generate predicted trajectories of proximate vehicles near the host vehicle based on a proposed trajectory for the host vehicle; compare the proposed trajectory for the host vehicle with the predicted trajectories of the proximate vehicles to determine whether a difference between the proposed trajectory for the host vehicle and the predicted trajectories of the proximate vehicle exceeds a minimum acceptable threshold; and decide whether to adjust speed or heading of the host vehicle based on whether the difference exceeds the minimum acceptable threshold. 35. The system of claim 34, wherein, if the comparison of the proposed trajectory for the host vehicle and the predicted trajectories of the proximate vehicle indicates the proposed trajectory for the host vehicle exceeds a minimum acceptable threshold, the proposed trajectory for the host vehicle is modified until the minimum acceptable threshold is satisfied. 36. The system of claim 35, wherein the predicted trajectories of proximate vehicles are generated based on training data including perception data corresponding to human driving behaviors from vehicles and drivers in real world traffic environments. 37. The system of claim 34, wherein the trajectory prediction generator includes a machine learning system that includes parameters trained based on context data in which the host vehicle is operating. 38. The system of claim 34, wherein the trajectory prediction includes an acceleration prediction obtained using a regression algorithm. 39. The system of claim 34, wherein the trajectory prediction generator is further configured to determine a confidence level corresponding to a likelihood of the proximate vehicles to take the predicted trajectories. 40. A computer program product comprising a non-transitory computer readable medium having executable instructions stored thereupon, the executable instructions, when executed, causing a processor to: generate a proposed trajectory for a host vehicle; generate predicted trajectories of proximate vehicles near the host vehicle based on a proposed trajectory for the host vehicle; compare the proposed trajectory for the host vehicle with the predicted trajectories of the proximate vehicles to determine whether a difference between the proposed trajectory for the host vehicle and the predicted trajectories of the proximate vehicle exceeds a minimum acceptable threshold; and decide whether to adjust speed or heading of the host vehicle based on whether the difference exceeds the minimum acceptable threshold. 41. The computer program product of claim 40, wherein, if the comparison of the proposed trajectory for the host vehicle and the predicted trajectories of the proximate vehicle indicates the proposed trajectory for the host vehicle exceeds a minimum acceptable threshold, the proposed trajectory for the host vehicle is modified until the minimum acceptable threshold is satisfied. 42. The computer program product of claim 41, wherein the predicted trajectories of proximate vehicles are generated based on training data including perception data corresponding to human driving behaviors from vehicles and drivers in real world traffic environments. 43. The computer program product of claim 40, wherein the trajectory prediction generator includes a machine learning system that includes parameters trained based on context data in which the host vehicle is operating. 44. The computer program product of claim 40, wherein the trajectory prediction includes an acceleration prediction obtained using a regression algorithm. 45. The computer program product of claim 40, wherein the trajectory prediction generator is further configured to determine a confidence level corresponding to a likelihood of the proximate vehicles to take the predicted trajectories.
